<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Standard Deviation and Variance</h1>=20


<p class=3D"center"><i>Deviation means how far from the normal</i></p>=20


<h2 id=3D"top">Standard Deviation</h2>=20

<p>The Standard Deviation  is a measure of how spread out numbers are.</p>=
=20
<p>Its symbol is <b class=3D"larger">=CF=83</b> (the greek letter sigma)</p=
>=20
<p>The formula is easy: it is the<b> square root</b> of the <b>Variance.</b=
> So now you ask, "What is the Variance?"</p>=20


<h2>Variance</h2>=20

<p>The Variance  is defined as:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center larger">The average of the <b>squared</b> differences fr=
om the Mean.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>To calculate the variance follow these steps:</p>=20
<ul class=3D"disc">=20
	<li>Calculate the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/mean.html">Mean</a=
> (the simple average of the numbers)</li>=20
	<li>Then for each number: subtract the Mean and  square the result (the <i=
>squared difference</i>).</li>=20
	<li>Then calculate the average of those squared differences. (<a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviation.html#WhySquare">Why Squar=
e?</a>)</li> =20

</ul>=20


<h2>Example</h2>=20

<p>You and your friends have just measured the heights of your dogs (in mil=
limeters):</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/stat=
istics-dogs-graph.gif" alt=3D"dogs on graph shoulder heights" style=3D"max-=
width:100%" height=3D"204" width=3D"612"></p>=20
<p>The heights (at the shoulders) are: 600 mm, 470 mm, 170 mm, 430 mm and 3=
00 mm.</p>=20
<p>Find out the Mean, the Variance, and the Standard Deviation.</p>=20
<p>Your first step is to find the Mean:</p>=20

<h3>Answer:</h3>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><span class=3D"larger">Mean</span></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:40px;"><span class=3D"larger">=3D<=
/span></td>
			<td class=3D"larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>600 + 470 + 170 + 430 + 3=
00</em><strong>5</strong></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:40px;"><span class=3D"larger">=3D<=
/span></td>
			<td class=3D"larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>1970</em><strong>5</stron=
g></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:center; width:40px;"><span class=3D"larger">=3D<=
/span></td>
			<td class=3D"larger">394</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20

<p>so the mean (average) height is 394 mm. Let's plot this on the chart:</p=
>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/stat=
istics-dogs-mean.gif" alt=3D"dogs on graph: mean" style=3D"max-width:100%" =
height=3D"207" width=3D"619"></p>=20
<p>Now we calculate each dog's difference from the Mean:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/stat=
istics-dogs-deviation.gif" alt=3D"dogs on graph: deviation" style=3D"max-wi=
dth:100%" height=3D"165" width=3D"618"></p>=20
<p>To calculate the Variance, take each difference, square it, and then ave=
rage the result:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td colspan=3D"3" class=3D"larger"><b>Variance</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">=CF=83<sup>2</sup></td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td class=3D"larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>206<sup>2</sup> + 76<sup>=
2</sup> + (=E2=88=92224)<sup>2</sup> + 36<sup>2</sup> + (=E2=88=9294)<sup>2=
</sup></em><strong>5</strong></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td class=3D"larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>42436 + 5776 + 50176 + 12=
96 + 8836</em><strong>5</strong></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td class=3D"larger"><span class=3D"intbl"><em>108520</em><strong>5</str=
ong></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger">&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td class=3D"larger">21704</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>So the Variance is <b>21.704</b></p>=20
<p>And the Standard Deviation is just the square root of Variance, so:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td colspan=3D"3"><span class=3D"center larger"><b>Standard Deviation</b=
></span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger">=CF=83 </span></td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger">=E2=88=9A21704 </span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger"> 147,32...</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td class=3D"larger center">=3D</td>
			<td><span class=3D"center larger"><b>147</b> <i>(to the nearest mm)</i><=
/span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>And the good thing about the Standard Deviation is that it is useful. No=
w we can show which heights are within one Standard Deviation (147 mm) of t=
he Mean:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/stat=
istics-standard-deviation.gif" alt=3D"dogs on graph: standard deviation" st=
yle=3D"max-width:100%" height=3D"208" width=3D"621"></p>=20
<p>So, using the Standard Deviation we have a "standard" way of knowing wha=
t is normal, and what is extra large or extra small.</p>=20
<p>Rottweilers <b>are</b> tall dogs. And Dachshunds <b>are</b> a bit short,=
 right?</p>=20


<h2>Using</h2>=20

<p style=3D"float:right; margin: 0 0 5px 10px;"><img src=3D"https://www.mat=
hsisfun.com/data/images/normal-distrubution-1sd.svg" alt=3D"normal distrubu=
tion 1 sd =3D 68%" height=3D"144" width=3D"300"></p>=20
<p>We can expect about 68% of values to be within plus-or-minus 1 standard =
deviation.</p>=20
<p>Read <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-normal-distribu=
tion.html">Standard Normal Distribution</a> to learn more.</p>=20
<p>Also try the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviati=
on-calculator.html">Standard Deviation Calculator</a>.</p>=20


<h2>But ... there is a small change with <b>Sample</b> Data</h2>=20

<p>Our example has been for a <b>Population</b> (the 5 dogs are the only do=
gs we are interested in).</p>=20
<p>But if the  data is  a <b>Sample</b> (a selection taken from a bigger Po=
pulation), then the calculation changes!</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"larger">When we have "N" data values that are:</p>=20
<div class=3D"bigul">=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>The Population</b>: divide by <b>N</b> when calculating Variance (l=
ike we did)</li>=20
	<li><b>A Sample</b>: divide by <b>N-1</b> when calculating Variance</li>=
=20
</ul>=20
</div>
</div>=20

<p><span class=3D"center">All  other calculations stay the same, including =
how we calculated the mean.</span></p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<p>Example: if our 5 dogs are just a <b>sample</b> of a bigger population =
of dogs, we  divide by <b>4 instead of 5</b> like this:</p>=20
	<div class=3D"so">Sample Variance =3D 108.520 / <span class=3D"hilite"><b>=
4</b></span> =3D <b>27.130</b></div>
<div class=3D"so">Sample Standard Deviation =3D =E2=88=9A27.130 =3D <b>165<=
/b> (to the nearest mm)</div>
</div>=20

<p>Think of it as a "correction" when our data is only a sample.</p>=20


<h2>Formulas</h2>=20

<p>Here are the two formulas,   explained at <a href=3D"https://www.mathsis=
fun.com/data/standard-deviation-formulas.html">Standard Deviation Formulas<=
/a> if you want to know more:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">=20
<p>The "<b>Population</b> Standard Deviation":</p></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-formula.svg" alt=3D"square root of [ (1/N) times Sigma i=3D1 to N of (xi =
- mu)^2 ]" height=3D"59" width=3D"200"></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">The "<b>Sample</b> Standard Deviation<b>=
":</b></td>
			<td style=3D"text-align:right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-sample.svg" alt=3D"square root of [ (1/(N-1)) times Sigma i=3D1 to N of (=
xi - xbar)^2 ]" height=3D"58" width=3D"210"></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p class=3D"center">Looks complicated, but the important change is to<br>
divide by <b>N-1</b> (instead of <b>N</b>) when calculating a Sample Standa=
rd Deviation.</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20

<h3 id=3D"WhySquare"><b>*Footnote: Why <i>square</i> the differences?</b></=
h3>=20

<p>If we just add up the differences from the mean ...  the negatives  canc=
el the positives:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-why-a.gif" alt=3D"standard deviation why a" height=3D"92" width=3D"118"><=
/td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"intbl"><em>4 + 4 =E2=88=92 4 =E2=88=92 4</em><strong>=
4</strong></span> =3D <span class=3D"hilite">0</span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>So that won't work. How about we use <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.c=
om/numbers/absolute-value.html">absolute values</a>?</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-why-a.gif" alt=3D"standard deviation why a" height=3D"92" width=3D"118"><=
/td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"intbl"> <em>|4| + |4| + |=E2=88=924| + |=E2=88=924|</=
em><strong>4</strong></span> =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>4 + 4 + 4 + 4</=
em> <strong>4</strong> </span> =3D <span class=3D"hilite">4</span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>That looks good (and is the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/m=
ean-deviation.html">Mean Deviation</a>), but what about this case:</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-why-b.gif" alt=3D"standard deviation why b" height=3D"125" width=3D"118">=
</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"intbl"> <em>|7| + |1| + |=E2=88=926| + |=E2=88=922|</=
em><strong>4</strong></span> =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>7 + 1 + 6 + 2</=
em> <strong>4</strong> </span> =3D <span class=3D"hilite">4</span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>Oh No! It also gives a value of 4, Even though the differences are  more=
 spread out.</p>=20
<p>So let us try squaring each difference (and taking the  square root at t=
he end):</p>

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-why-a.gif" alt=3D"standard deviation why a" height=3D"92" width=3D"118"><=
/td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td> <span class=3D"lg">=E2=88=9A(</span><span class=3D"intbl"> <em>4<su=
p>2</sup> + 4<sup>2</sup> + (-4)<sup>2</sup> + (-4)<sup>2</sup></em><strong=
>4</strong></span><span class=3D"lg">)</span> =3D <span class=3D"lg">=E2=88=
=9A(</span><span class=3D"intbl"> <em>64</em> <strong>4</strong> </span><sp=
an class=3D"lg">)</span> =3D <span class=3D"hilite">4</span></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/images/standard-deviatio=
n-why-b.gif" alt=3D"standard deviation why b" height=3D"125" width=3D"118">=
</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><span class=3D"lg">=E2=88=9A(</span><span class=3D"intbl"> <em>7<sup=
>2</sup> + 1<sup>2</sup> + (-6)<sup>2</sup> + (-2)<sup>2</sup></em> <strong=
>4</strong></span><span class=3D"lg">)</span> =3D <span class=3D"lg">=E2=88=
=9A(</span><span class=3D"intbl"> <em>90</em> <strong>4</strong> </span><sp=
an class=3D"lg">)</span> =3D <span class=3D"hilite">4,74...</span></td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
<p>That is nice! The  Standard Deviation is bigger when  the differences ar=
e more spread out  ... just what we want.</p>=20
<p>In fact this method is a similar idea to  <a href=3D"https://www.mathsis=
fun.com/algebra/distance-2-points.html">distance between points</a>, just a=
pplied in a different way.</p>=20
<p>And it is  easier to use algebra on squares and square roots than absolu=
te values, which makes the standard deviation easy to use in other areas of=
 mathematics.</p>=20
<p><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/standard-deviation.html#Top">=
Return to Top</a></p>=20
